## Key Domain Flows

### Flow 1: Personal Event Creation

```
User in Slack: "@CoAgent4U add gym tomorrow at 7 AM"
  │
  ▼
SlackInboundAdapter → HandleMessageUseCase (agent-module)
  │
  ▼
IntentParser (rule-based, then LLM fallback) → ParsedIntent
  │
  ▼
ConflictDetector → checks CalendarPort for overlaps
  │
  ├─ No conflict → create Approval (approval-module)
  │                    │
  │                    ▼
  │              Slack notification to user: [Approve] / [Reject]
  │                    │
  │                    ▼
  │              User approves → CalendarPort.createEvent()
  │              → Confirmation sent
  │
  └─ Conflict found → notify user with conflict details
                       → user decides: add anyway or cancel
```

### Flow 2: Two-User Collaborative Scheduling

```
User A: "@CoAgent4U schedule meeting with @UserB on Friday evening"
  │
  ▼
Agent A: parse intent → check A's availability via CalendarPort
  │
  ▼
CoordinationProtocolPort → Coordination State Machine (14 states)
  │
  ├─ INITIATED
  ├─ CHECKING_AVAILABILITY_A → Agent A's free slots
  ├─ CHECKING_AVAILABILITY_B → Agent B's free slots (via AgentAvailabilityPort)
  ├─ MATCHING → AvailabilityMatcher finds overlap
  ├─ PROPOSAL_GENERATED → ProposalGenerator picks earliest slot
  ├─ AWAITING_APPROVAL_B → User B gets [Approve]/[Reject]
  ├─ AWAITING_APPROVAL_A → User A gets [Approve]/[Reject]
  ├─ APPROVED_BY_BOTH
  ├─ CREATING_EVENT_B → EventCreationSaga creates in B's calendar
  ├─ CREATING_EVENT_A → Saga creates in A's calendar
  └─ COMPLETED (or REJECTED / FAILED with saga compensation)
```

> [!NOTE]
> If event creation fails for User B after User A's event was already created, the **saga compensation** deletes User A's event automatically.

